                be held in June and done quickly; (2) Common Core. It was noted that there was an unprecedented amount of topics suggested for study this
                year. Over 140 topics were suggested or mandated. Caucus leaders explained the process they used to prioritize these issues and emphasized
                that Committee Chairmen still have discretion to add topics. Speaker Bosma hinted that he would talk to his members about an "informal new
                rule" that in the future bills with summer study language in them would have to be discretionary not mandatory.
            </p>
            <p>Of the topics described in the <a href="http://library.constantcontact.com/download/get/file/1109130244637-120/2013+Summer+Study+Topics.pdf" class="newsletter-inline" target="_blank">resolution</a>,
                the only items of potential concern are the following, which will likely include broadband issues. </p>
            <ul class="newsletter-list-1">
                <li>IC 2-5-31.8-3, the interim study committee on economic development shall study the following in 2013:</li>
                <li>(1) Fostering entrepreneurship in rural areas of Indiana.</li>
                <li>(2) Attracting new businesses to rural areas of Indiana.</li>
                <li>(3) Attracting venture capital to rural areas of Indiana.</li>
                <li>(4) Expanding existing businesses in rural areas of Indiana.</li>
                <li>(5) Promoting gainful employment opportunities and workforce development in rural areas of Indiana.</li>
                <li>(b) The interim study committee on economic development shall submit its findings and recommendations, if any, on the topics
                    assigned under subsection (a) to the legislative council in an electronic format before November 1, 2013.</li>
                <li>(c) This SECTION expires January 1, 2013.</li>
            </ul>

            <p>Also, the "Ag Gag" language is in the Economic Development Committee's Section E- Trespassing for the purpose of
                harming a business, and making video images of a business with the intent to falsely portray the operations of a business.</p>
            <p>The Legislative Council also announced that the General Assembly would be meeting for a technical corrections day on June 12th and will be considering a veto override for
                HB1546.</p>
