            <section class="newsletter-subsection">
                <h4>New Indiana Laws In Effect</h4>
                <p>
                    Usually, except for in emergency instances when bills take effect immediately upon passage, new laws take effect every July 1st.  Here is a brief summary of some of our new laws as of July 1.</p>


                <p><span class="bold">Healthcare:</span>  Pharmacists can now give additional vaccines besides flu shots; including tetanis, diptheria, pneumonia, acellular pertussis, HPV and meningitis vaccinations.  Also, now you no longer need a referral in order to see a physical therapist, and certified midwifery became legal.</p>
                <p><span class="bold">Law Enforcement & Courts:</span> Criminal record expungement for non-violent minor felonies and misdemeanors can now be requested after 5-8 years.  The minimum penalty for illegally parking in a spot marked for those with disabilities doubled from $50 to $100, and Indiana joins the Blue Alert System that will notify the public when a police officer is missing, injured or killed in the line of duty.</p>
                <p><span class="bold">Education:</span>  Teachers will receive training on how to spot signs of bullying and will be required to report instances to administrators and parents.  For-profit companies can now participate in college work-study programs; All participating employers must offer "resume-building" jobs and receive clearance from the Commission for Higher Education.  Also in new education laws, high schools are now required to test juniors at risk of failing their graduation exam or being prepared for basic college prep work; and finally, Students whose local public school is rated "F" by the state or have a sibling attending private school using a state voucher can obtain a voucher without first attending public school for a year, if income limits are met.</p>
                <p><span class="bold">Department of Child Services:</span>  The child protection agency will get an additional $35 million to hire more staffers for the state's child abuse hotline. Three new commissions designed to improve the department, including one dedicated to investigating suspicious child deaths, are to begin meeting. Prosecutors can now ask judges to intervene on behalf of an abused child if DCS chooses not to. </p>

